Pop the @diced chicken thigh{260%g} into a #bowl{} with the @cider vinegar{15%ml} and half the @Goan Xacuti spice{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}, stir together and set aside.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken.

Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add @salt{0.25%tsp}, stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces). Peel and grate the @ginger{1/2%tsp}(grated). Halve the @red chilli{1}(halved and deseeded) lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} over medium high heat. Once hot add the chicken and stir fry until golden brown all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the onion and cook until soft, a further ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the garlic, chilli, ginger and remaining Goan curry powder. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

> TIP: Add less curry powder and chilli if you don't like heat - they are very spicy!

Add the @tomato passata{1%tsp}, @water for the curry{100%ml}, @chicken stock powder{1%tsp}, @tomato puree{30%g} and @honey{15%ml} to the pan with the chicken. Season with salt and pepper, bring to a simmer and cook until thick and tomatoey, ~{7-9%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the curry a handful at a time until wilted. Bring to the boil and simmer until the sauce has reduced slightly and the flavours have developed, ~{3-4%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper if you like.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between bowls. Top with the curry and enjoy!